4. Monogamy of quantum correlations for the three-particle W -class state under decoherence
In order to use quantum correlations as a resource, we are faced with the problem of their distribution through a multipar-

100306-4

Chin. Phys. B Vol. 22, No. 10 (2013) 100306

tite state. In a multipartite setting, an important property for quantum entanglement is monogamy. The monogamy means that in multiparty quantum states, if two subsystems are highly entangled, then they would not share a substantial amount of quantum entanglement with other subsystems.[48â€“55] Due to the interest aroused by the monogamy of quantum entanglement, several quantum phenomena have been discovered that the generalized Greenbergerâ€“Horneâ€“Zeilinger (GHZ) states[56] always meet the monogamy of quantum discord, while the generalized W states[57] always infringe it. Here we give a multipartite state Ï12Â·Â·Â·n shared among N parties, the monogamy condition in the multipartite state could be expressed as the following inequality

D (Ï12) + D (Ï13) + Â· Â· Â· + D (Ï1n) â‰¤ D (Ï1:23Â·Â·Â·n) . (17)

Here Ï12 = tr34Â·Â·Â·n Ï12Â·Â·Â·n. On the right-hand side of the above inequality, the quantity D (Ï1:23Â·Â·Â·n) is the same quantum correlation measures as those obtained in the bipartition 1 : 23 Â· Â· Â· n of the N parties.
Besides the above work, particularly, we want to investigate whether the monogamy inequality for the three-particle W -class class state will be satisï¬ed. For the tripartite system |W 123, the monogamy inequality is

D Ï12 + D Ï13 â‰¤ D Ï1:23 .

(18)

As is well known, generalized W states under the ideal channel do not follow the monogamy. Interestingly, we ï¬nd that the quantum discord of the three-particle W -class states under the phase ï¬‚ip channel could invariably satisfy the monogamy. In order to illustrate it in more detail, we calculate a crowd of ecumenical W -class states and choose some random states in Fig. 5.

5. Conclusions
In this paper, we study the various quantum correlations for three-particle W -class states, given by the entanglement of formation and QD, between arbitrary two atoms. We ï¬nd an interesting phenomenon between the QD and the EOF under the decoherence, given by two atoms, and also ï¬nd that the QD is not always larger than the entanglement and the phenomenon may affect the use of the quantum correlations. In our analysis, the critical point appearing wherein the quantum correlations of two atoms is at a maximum under the phase ï¬‚ip channel. For the three-particle W -class states, we also ï¬nd that when only atom 1 is in the decoherence channel, D Ï12 and D Ï13 are affected by the decoherence parameter p, and the D Ï23 is impervious. It is similar to atom 2 and atom 3. If atom 1 and atom 2 are both in the phase ï¬‚ip channel, the inï¬‚uence on the D Ï12 outweighs the D Ï13 and D Ï23 . The D Ï12 , D Ï13 , and D Ï23 have the same inï¬‚uence by the decoherence with considering all the three atoms to be in the decoherence environment. On the other hand, we show that the critical coefï¬cient can be one that makes the loss of entanglement in the Werner state. Monogamy as an important aspect of quantum entanglement means that this â€œinvaluableâ€ resource could not be freely sharable. Inspired by this, we study the monogamy of the W -class states in the phase ï¬‚ip channel, which always satisï¬es the monogamy. One of the major obstacles to building an efï¬cient quantum computer is the presence of errors introduced by the environment. In short, we know more characteristics about the different quantum correlations, and we could use them better. We hope and will make sure that more and more work associated with this will be done in the future.

